Notification Service
Problem Statement
Build a backend service that sends notifications (e.g. emails).
 Clients can register templates and enqueue notifications based on those templates.
 The service must avoid duplicate notifications using an idempotencyKey.
You can use any backend language/framework.
 For this round, it is OK to use in-memory data structures instead of a real database. We will discuss database design separately.

Requirements
1. Data Model (in-memory is fine)
You need to maintain:
A list/map of templates, each with:


id
name
channel (e.g. "EMAIL")
subject
body


A list/map of notifications, each with:
id
templateName
recipient
data (JSON object with template variables)
status (e.g. "PENDING", "SENT")
idempotencyKey
attempts (number)



2. APIs to Implement
a) Register Template
POST /templates
Request body (example):

 {
  "name": "ORDER_CREATED",
  "channel": "EMAIL",
  "subject": "Your order {{orderId}} is confirmed",
  "body": "Hi {{userName}}, your order {{orderId}} is confirmed."
}


Behavior:
Validate required fields (name, channel, subject, body).
Create a template with a unique id and store it.
Response: created template (including id).


b) Enqueue Notification
POST /notifications
Request body (example):

 {
  "templateName": "ORDER_CREATED",
  "recipient": "user@example.com",
  "data": {
    "orderId": "o999",
    "userName": "Alice"
  },
  "idempotencyKey": "order-created-o999"
}


Behavior:
Validate required fields (templateName, recipient, data, idempotencyKey).
Check that a template with templateName exists:
If not → return 400.
Check if a notification with the same idempotencyKey already exists:
If yes → return the existing notification (do not create a duplicate).
If no → create and store a new notification with:
status = "PENDING"
attempts = 0
Response: notification object (new or existing).


c) Process Pending Notifications
POST /notifications/process
Behavior:

Find all notifications with status = "PENDING".
For each:
“Send” it by printing/logging something to the console (no real email needed).
Set status = "SENT" and increment attempts.
Return a summary (e.g. how many notifications were processed).


d) Get Notification Status
GET /notifications/:id
Look up the notification by id.

If found → return it.

If not found → return 404.



3. Testing
Write a few unit tests for core behavior, for example:
Enqueue a notification with a valid template → PENDING notification is created.

Enqueue again with the same idempotencyKey → no duplicate is created.

Processing pending notifications changes status from PENDING to SENT.

4. Notes
You do not need to integrate real email/SMS providers.
You do not need to implement retry/backoff logic; just a simple “process once” is enough.
We will discuss idempotency, DB design, and reliability in more depth after the coding part
